<section xml:id="sec-integration-by-substitution">
  <title>Integration by substitution</title>

  <objectives>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          Reverse the Chain Rule by introducing a substitution to simplify the integrand.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Adjust limits of integration after changing variables in definite integrals.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Use multi-stage substitutions for more complicated expressions.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </objectives>
  
  <introduction>
    <p>
      Introduction goes here.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <ul>
    <li>
      <p>
        This is the <q>Anti-Chain Rule</q>: making the substitution <m>u=g(x)</m> and <m>\dd u=g'(x)\dd{x}</m> gives
        <me>
          \int f(g(x))g'(x)\dd{x}=\int f(u)\dd{u}
        </me>
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Transforming definite integrals:
        <aside>
          <p>
            According to <em>Advanced Calculus</em> by James J. Callahan, this is a pushforward substitution!
          </p>
        </aside>
        <me>
          \int_{a}^{b} f(g(x))g'(x)\dd{x}=\int_{g(a)}^{g(b)}f(u)\dd{u}
        </me>
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Look at examples where multiple substitutions are needed, such as
        <me>
          \int x\sqrt{x+1}\dd{x}
        </me>
      </p>
    </li>
  </ul>
</section>
